n the history of popular music. The essays collated here locate The Clash in their own explosive cultural moment of punk's year zero and examine how the group speaks from beyond the grave to the uncanny parallels of other moments of social and political crisis. In addition, the collection considers the impact of the band in a range of different geopolitical contexts, with various contributors exploring what the band meant in settings as diverse as Italy, England, Northern Ireland, Australia and the United States. The diverse essays gathered in Working for the clampdown cast a critical light on both the cultural legacy and contemporary resonance of one of the most influential bands ever to have graced a stage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPunk rock musicxHistory and criticism. 0aPunk rock musicxPolitical aspects. 0aPunk rock musicianszEnglandvBiography. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  a1970s London.  aGlobal culture.  aPolitics and music.  aPopular music.  aPunk misic.  aPunk music.  aRadical politics.  aThe Clash.1 aAdams, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBottà, Giacomo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrowne, Harry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrunström, Conrad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCashell, Kieran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoon, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoulter, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoulter, Colin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDale, Pete, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4